english:
  title: In Response to Scholar Lee's Inscribed Poem at Goshan Station
  author: Im Yujeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A sudden messenger brings word—horses and carriages arriving at the stream's eastern shore.
    I rein in at the station inn, standing alone, leaning against the railing.
    Clouds rise on the eastern peak while the western ridge gleams white.
    This year the blossoms burn more crimson than last year's flowers.
    Half-drawn are the curtains through the depths of autumn night.
    Above the tower, the setting sun accompanies a flute's wandering music.
    Fortunate am I to have mountains and waters offering their finest views.
    Climbing and gazing, my verses flow—thoughts stretch on without end.
  footnotes:
    - This poem is composed of eight lines, each attributed to a different poet or figure, following a poetic game tradition where multiple poets collaborate by each contributing a couplet or line in response to an initial theme or inscription.
